In article <1nql2k$2rv@transfer.stratus.com> cme@ellisun.sw.stratus.com (Carl Ellison) writes:
>In article <C3qoun.EtH@cpqhou.se.hou.compaq.com> jlund@cpqhou.se.hou.compaq.com (John Lund) writes:
>
>>I have also recently wondered if a system of metaphoric language could be
>>utilized in key transmission over regular phone lines between persons
>>only familiar with the metaphors being invoked.
>
>This reminds me of something I tried in the past but won't do again because
>it's such hard work.

From popular true crime books, I have learned that this system is commonly
used by organized crime. To defeat wire tapping, metaphors and obtuse
descriptions are used instead of clear language. 

Somebody carrying guns from Florida may only be refered to as "the guy
down south with the goods". 

The terms are obscure and varied enough that even the conversants sometimes have
difficulty following the thread of the conversation.
